    "An exemplary sketch of how RNN generates an expression (e.g., x 2cos(x)) is shown in Fig. 16.",
    "Starting with the first node fol- lowing the pre-order traversal (Sect. 2.2) of an expression tree, RNN is initially fed with empty placeholders tokens (a parent and a sibling) and produces a categorical distribution, i.e., outputs the probability of selecting every token from the defined library L = {+, -, ×, ÷, sin, cos, log, etc.}",
    "The sampled token is fed into the first node, and the number of siblings is determined based on whether the operation is unary (one sibling) or Page 25 of 38 2",
    "binary (two siblings).",
    "The second node is then selected, and the RNN is fed with internal weights along with the first token and outputs a new (and potentially different) categorical distribution."
